      {
        "id": 3930447,
        "name": "Alex Goldstein",
        "username": "Alex_Goldstein",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/9de053/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2022-11-12T19:31:48.197Z",
        "cooked": "<p>A bit of a mystery I am hoping the Berserkers can help me solve\u2026</p>\n<p>I ordered this wine and 18 months later was delivered a wine with the label \u201cPremier Jus\u201d but not \u201cHauts des Vignes\u201d. The retailer informed me that Hauts des Vignes was not in fact made in 2019, and I received the correct cuvee.</p>\n<p>CellarTracker notes both cuvees being made in 2019. However, the label for Hauts des Vignes is borrowed from the 2018 vintage, so I haven\u2019t got proof the wine was made in 2019.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, William Kelley rated \u201c2019 Pouilly-Fuiss\u00e9 1er Jus des Hautes des Vignes\u201d twice. I find it difficult to believe that the exceptionally thorough William Kelly twice reviewed a wine that didn\u2019t exist.</p>\n<p>The only thing I could think of is that after William\u2019s second review the winery decide to change the name of the cuvee for some reason. It seems unlikely, but possible.</p>\n<p>Does anyone have any insight into this mystery? Has anyone physically put their hands on a bottle of 2019 labeled Haut des Vignes?</p>\n<p>Any help solving this mystery would be greatly appreciated. <img src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/images/emoji/unicode/pray.png?v=12\" title=\":pray:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":pray:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\"></p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 5,
